Schema, decoded from gap_analysis.pdf's Configuration_Guide screenshot — model_type: "custom" takes both model_path (.pth weights) and source_path (Python module). That was the missing piece.

Three things worth flagging before you run:

    The wrapper exposes five entry-point names (create_model, get_model, build_model, load_model, MODEL) all bound to the same factory. The exact name the toolkit's loader looks for isn't visible in any artifact reviewed. Defensive coverage is cheap; cycle time on a "name not found" failure is not. If it still misses, grep pytorch_to_executorch_vision.py for the expected symbol and add one more alias.
    Run test_wrapper_smoke.py before the toolkit. It does torch.export on the wrapper end-to-end with the real weights. If it fails, the toolkit will fail for the same reason — and you'll see a stack trace from your own code instead of from inside the toolkit's loader. ~30 seconds, isolates blame.
    INT8 PTQ calibration is opaque. The config schema we've seen has no calibration field, so the toolkit is almost certainly calibrating on random tensors. That's fine for producing the artifact but unreliable as a quality signal for SSD's regression head. Capture the parity delta but don't gate on it — flag as follow-up.

