What the loader actually does (Image 8–13)

ModelLoaderBase.load_custom_model(model_path, model_class=None, source_path=None):

    source_path is a directory that gets prepended to sys.path (sys.path.insert(0, source_path)). It exists so pickle can resolve custom classes during torch.load. It is not a factory module. The toolkit never calls a function in it.
    torch.load(model_path) with weights_only=True first, falling back to weights_only=False. The thing on disk must be either a complete nn.Module or a state-dict with model_class provided. The vision configs we can see (CRAFT, SRGAN, Inception) have no model_class field, so the convention is save a complete model object.
    CRAFT is the right analog — source_path: ".../model_sources/CRAFT" (directory), model_path: ".../weights/craft_ic15_20k.pth" (complete model file).

So all the factory aliases, the create_model/get_model/MODEL defensive coverage, the smoke test that called a factory — none of that maps to anything. Trash.
Real plan, three files

    Wrapper module — defines MobileNetV2SSDLiteWrapper. Module-level side effect adds pytorch-ssd/ to sys.path so the inner SSD class resolves during unpickling. That's all it does.
    One-time build script — load qfgaohao state-dict → wrap → torch.save(wrapper, ...) as a complete model file.
    Config — modeled exactly on the CRAFT config you showed me. Two INT8 variants (per-tensor and per-channel), calibration uses the 10 COCO sample images.

